Most people in Portugal (86%) want conception to be punishable for women and abortion doctors alike.74 The pro-life activist Inês de Medeiros explains the situation well in the following quote:
“Right now legislation states that under special circumstances the government will decide about the fate of an abortion. It is just a trick. The Tribunal can decide whether or not to authorize an abortion, but it is not in our constitution because if it was there, we could pass a referendum and stop the Tribunal from approving the decision to kill an innocent life… I understand that there are two huge problems in Portuguese society: abortion and euthanasia….Don’t you think that there will be many more abortions if we decriminalize it? The current regime, in my opinion, does not respect the value of human life. All of these things defeat me. I feel the guilt.”75 Whatever one’s position on abortion, people do themselves an injustice by ignoring the truth about abortion’s consequences. Statistics highlight the burgeoning impact of abortion on women. People seem more and more aware of the debilitating effects of abortion on women, advances in modern medical science detail the damage abortion causes to the body and the spirit. Perinatal hospice and adoption program expose the truth about abortion. Continued use of contraception and abortion as a family planning tool will lead to societies more progressive with ever
